es. It includes radical proposals for reform of the curriculum and how we admit students to higher education, with part-time study (currently in crisis in England) becoming the norm. A short, polemical but also deeply practical book, Who are universities for? offers concrete solutions to the problems facing UK higher education and a way forward for universities to become more inclusive and more responsive to local and global challenges.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEducation, HigherxEconomic aspectszGreat Britain. 0aEducation, HigherzGreat Britain. 0aEducation, Higher. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh1 aMcLellan, Josie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPettigrew, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z9783111196664oZDB-23-BUPP0 cprintz978152920038640uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781529200393?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781529200393423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781529200393/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-BUPPb2018